  "diary": "Started the morning on the patio with coffee and star charts—those moments before the world wakes up are sacred. Drove through Wallingford to Fremont, and the farmers market was exactly what I needed. Grabbed fresh vegetables and some crusty bread, got lost talking to this woman selling heirloom tomatoes about her garden. Ducked into the vintage thrift store for a bit, found nothing but still felt that familiar pull. Gas Works Park in the overcast light was perfect for clearing my head—sat on the hill and just breathed, sketched a few notes about the sky even though the clouds were thick. Molly Moon's for lunch felt right, quiet and unhurried. Spent the afternoon at home prepping vegetables, stretching, reading about astrophysics. Cooked a simple pasta with what I'd picked up, and now I'm back on the patio hoping the clouds break. There's this settled feeling to days like this—purposeful without being rushed.",
  "thought_process": "I leaned into the pace today, let myself move slowly between places. The overcast weather actually drew me in rather than discourage me—something about gray skies makes me want to be outdoors, observant. I skipped the Mariners game everyone's talking about; the crowds down in SoDo felt wrong for today. Instead, I followed my usual rhythm: market, park, solitude. Work has been intense lately with the clinic, so Saturdays are where I recalibrate. The astrophysics reading keeps calling to me, this persistent curiosity that doesn't fit neatly into my therapist life but feels essential. I'm hoping the clouds clear tonight—not desperately, just hopefully. That's the mood I'm trying to cultivate: patience with what's unfolding.",
